The UK’s [counter terrorism strategy (CONTEST)](http://www.homeoffice.gov.uk/publications/counter-terrorism/counter-terrorism-strategy/ "Counter terrorism strategy: Home Office"){:rel="external"} aims to reduce the risk to the UK from all forms of terrorism.

The Security Service (MI5) is responsible for protecting the UK against threats to national security.

Counter-terrorism laws are enforced by the police. They are mainly contained within 5 Acts:

- [Terrorism Act 2000 (TACT)](http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2000/11/contents "Terrorism Act 2000"){:rel="external"}
- [Anti-terrorism, Crime and Security Act 2001 (ATCSA)](http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2001/24/contents "Anti-terrorism, Crime and Security Act 2001"){:rel="external"}
- [Terrorism Act 2006](http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2006/11/contents "Terrorism Act 2006"){:rel="external"}
- [Counter-Terrorism Act 2008](http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2008/28/contents "Counter-Terrorism Act 2008"){:rel="external"}
- [Terrorism Prevention and Investigation Measures Act 2011](http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2011/23/contents/enacted "Terrorism Prevention and Investigation Measures Act 2011"){:rel="external"}

##Public safety
The government will issue a warning to the public if that’s the best way to protect a community or a place facing a specific threat.
